\begin{abstract}

Dual-energy computed tomography (DECT) can be used to acquire an electron-density and an effective-atomic-number image of the scanned object. We show that a simple one-parametric formula for the electron density follows from a basic assumption on the functional form of the cross section. This assumption is valid in the energy range relevant to a CT scanner and in the atomic number range relevant to human tissue. We propose a robust calibration for the electron-density equation, which is easily applicable using standard equipment, and provide parameters for two clinical DECT scanners. For the application in proton and ion radiation therapy, we suggest to use the relative cross section instead of the effective atomic number, as it enables a proper treatment of tissue mixtures, while providing the same contrast for diagnostic or delineation purposes.

\end{abstract}





\vspace{2pc}
\noindent{\it Keywords}: proton and ion radiation therapy, effective atomic number, computed tomography




\maketitle






\section{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}

It was recognized by \citeasnoun{Rutherford1976} that under certain conditions and approximations, two CT scans, acquired with well-separated X-ray spectra, are sufficient to determine the electron density and effective atomic number of the scanned material. Since the clinical launch of dual-energy computed tomography (DECT), this method is, besides many diagnostic applications, of particular interest for radiotherapy, where it can supersede heuristic CT calibration via Hounsfield look-up tables and thereby decrease treatment planning uncertainties for both conventional photon therapy \cite{Saito2012} and particle therapy \cite{Yang2010,Huenemohr2014a}. Outside the medical field, CT-based material characterization is used for explosives detection among others \cite{Ying2006}.

A number of methods for electron-density and effective-atomic-number determination with a clinical DECT scanner have been proposed \cite{Bazalova2008,Saito2012,Landry2013,Bourque2014,Huenemohr2014a,Abbema2015}. They differ widely in the level of complexity concerning the underlying parameterization of the cross section, and in the number of required scanner properties, theoretical coefficients and calibration parameters. \citeasnoun{Huenemohr2014a} derived particularly simple, yet effective, equations for both electron density and effective atomic number, using a commercial algorithm (\textsc{syngo.via} DE Rho/Z Maps, Siemens Healthcare, Forchheim, Germany). Here, we generalize their approach, resulting in a procedure for the robust estimation of the electron density with a calibration method that is easily applicable.



