\Tref{tab:overview} lists important properties of the selected published algorithms cited in \sref{sec:intro}. \Eref{eq:RED_1param} for the determination of the relative electron density is equivalent to \citeasnoun[eq. 1]{Saito2012} and \citeasnoun[eq. 14]{Huenemohr2014a}. 
Whereas the first postulated the equation without derivation, the latter derived it from a parameterization of the cross section with the specific form $Z^m/E^3$ for the photoelectric term. As shown above, however, any form of \eref{eq:cross_section_basic} is sufficient to determine the relative electron density. Particular knowledge on $f(Z)$, e.g. in the form of an exponent parameter $m$ is not required and the energy dependence is absorbed in the calibration parameter $\alpha$. However, if the effective atomic number is determined first, as indicated in the column ``{\ensuremath{\widehat{n}}\xspace}/{\ensuremath{Z_\textrm{eff}}\xspace}'' of \tref{tab:overview}, the calculation of {\ensuremath{\widehat{n}}\xspace} might be biased by the constraint set from a specific choice for the definition of {\ensuremath{Z_\textrm{eff}}\xspace}.

Furthermore, as \eref{eq:cross_section_basic} is a necessary condition for the definition of a single effective atomic number, the usage of a more complex parameterization for its determination might add complexity in the calibration and application of the method without improvement in accuracy. This is supported by the fact that, according to \tref{tab:overview}, the accuracy does not improve for approaches using parameterizations not respecting \eref{eq:cross_section_basic}.




\section{Conclusion}

The measurement of relative electron density based on DECT requires a specific form of the functional dependency of the photon absorption cross section on energy and atomic number. In conjunction with the straightforward possibility to calibrate the single parameter $\alpha$ from data, we consider the DECT-based electron-density determination universal and robust within the limits of validity.

The determination of an energy-independent effective atomic number, however, is more complicated and requires more input. We therefore suggest to work with relative cross sections instead of effective atomic numbers. In combination with the calculation of the electron density, these can be directly inferred from DECT images without further necessity of a particular calibration.





